There is an overwhelming acceptance by experts in psychiatry that antidepressant medication (ADM) is useful for the maintenance treat- ment of adults with major depressive disorder (MDD). The primary basis for this is the many (> 70) industry sponsored, placebo sub- stitution (randomized withdrawal) trials which follow a set protocol. First, restrictively (enriched) screened samples of adults diagnosed with MDD are entered into an open ADM efficacy trial. Then the responders are urged to enter into a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled (RDBPC) maintenance trial. At the beginning of this trial, known as a placebo substitution trial, about a third of the ADM responders are abruptly switched to placebo, whereas the other responders continue on the ADM that benefited them. The consistent result of these main- tenance trials is that those switched to placebo experience a relapse rate two or more times the rate of responders who were maintained on their antidepressant medication[69].

However, there are other ADM randomized, controlled maintenance methodologies that present different MDD relapse outcomes. A total of five (including placebo substitution) published maintenance meth- odologies will be presented and relapse rates from their treatment trials will be detailed and compared. The totality of maintenance findings raise doubt about the value of placebo substitution trials to provide the primary rationale for antidepressant long term treatment, and ad- ditionally reveal that the issues encompassing ADM maintenance for adults diagnosed with MDD are very complex[69].
